[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Researchers at Meta have made a distressingly accurate AI model of a brain that may be the future of cognition and artificial intelligence. It is so accurate that it can mimic cognition, so what a human brain should do even in situations that it\'s never'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'been in and we\'ll talk about it. This is Tribe version 2. It is the second iteration in these experiments. It\'s actually three models stitched together. It has an audio and a visual model as well as one that processes text, so the'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ones that a lot of us use more often. It was trained on thousands of hours of fMRI data. So, if you look at the activity in somebody\'s brain while they\'re doing things like speaking or reading or watching a movie or listening'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to language, that can then be translated into something that the model can understand. This is meant as a foundational model, so it should be able to process a broad data set and it\'s not meant for just one narrow area like a'

[00:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lot of this field is. Our brains are not meant to just take in one piece of sensory information in isolation. While you may notice something in front of you, you\'re also taking in balance information. You\'re taking in sound and sight and different parts of your brain'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are processing them simultaneously. And interestingly, that is exactly what they found in this paper. Even though they didn\'t explicitly model the lobes of the brain, they found that activity was activated for faces, for example, in the'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fusiform gyrus. They were able to demonstrate independently that their research is working. They are accurately modeling the areas of the brain. And unlike a lot of brain models, this also included a language element, which means'

[01:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yes, this could be fashioned in a way that you could talk to it and that fascinates me and I really want to. Another major accomplishment for them is that they could predict more than just the minds of the people that it was trained on. If you take a large'

[01:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'collection of human data and you average it, you get something that looks approximately human. We do find that with just standard LLMs. If you take all of mankind\'s knowledge and put it in a blender, it spits out something that sounds a warming way human. It was able'

[01:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to predict how a new person would react to a movie that they nor the person had ever seen This kind of research has a huge number of implications in a number of areas that it can be applied to. Some of them more unsettling than others. In'

[02:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'research, for example, if you have a reliable model of a human brain, that\'s something that you can run experiments on that aren\'t actually people. One of the areas that I find rather unsettling is advertisement because if you have a perfect model for a human brain, then'

[02:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'every advertisement is going to be perfectly made to elicit an emotional reaction and to make you want to buy it. And media will only be made if they\'re sure that people have the right emotional reaction. This will really'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'homogenize a lot of what\'s being made and I guess we are already seeing that. This paper was down a similar path. This is Centaur in training language models on human behavior and human actions.'

[02:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that they could reliably predict human cognition using them. They also did some interesting transformations in which they took fMRI data and translated that into something that an LLM could model.'

[02:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then they found out that just training AI on human behaviors does make them align very similarly to how human cognition works. It is not the way that a human brain works, but it can be'

[03:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'translated into actions that look very similar to ours. And of course, this has a huge number of implications for robotics. Now, I\'d really like to see what it looks like in an embodied robot. Right now, these sorts of models require a huge amount of resources and it\'s just'

[03:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not feasible to scale it down into a skull. But if you remember what computers looked like even 30 years ago, yeah. We figured that out. I am willing to keep an open mind. The'

[03:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'substrate of consciousness as we know it has been neurons because we\'ve only ever seen neurons that evolved on Earth. If information processing systems could develop intelligence, they don\'t necessarily need to look exactly like'

[03:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'us, but I guess it would be a little bit narcissistic to think that humans could really create intelligence, but I sure want to see if we can. Now, to give a slightly different perspective, many researchers believe that the marriage of'

[03:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
